Project: TMDb movie data analysis¶

Table of Contents¶

  • Introduction
  • Data Wrangling
  • Exploratory Data Analysis
  • Conclusions

This project use tmdb-movies.csv dataset.

Introduction¶

This data set contains information about 10,000 movies collected from The Movie Database (TMDb), including user ratings and revenue.

The first question is: Which genres are most popular from year to year?

With this question I want to see the most popular genre by it's mean in each year, and at the end see the genre with the most popularity of all of those.

The Second question is: What kinds of properties are associated with movies that have high revenues?

With this question I want to see, how much is the difference between movies that have high revenues and normal ones by it's propeties.

Function to split the string to be multiple values in the same touple to be the number of those values, that way it's easy and faster to manipulate the datas.

In [15]:
def drop_na_of_a_column(df,column_name):
    df_copy = df.copy()
    df_copy[column_name].dropna(axis=0,inplace=True)
In [16]:
"""
Split the string in multiple rows
"""
def split_string_in_multiple_rows(df, column_name, separator = '|'):
    
    index = df.set_index(df.columns.drop(column_name, 1).tolist())
    reseted_index = index[column_name].str.split(separator, expand=True).stack().reset_index()
    splited_df = reseted_index.rename(columns={0:column_name}).loc[:,df.columns]
    return splited_df

def show_max_genrer_year_by_year_chart(plt_chart):
    plt_size(20,5)
    genres_max_year_by_year = df_max_pop_year_by_year.genres.unique()
    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    for color, genre in enumerate(genres_max_year_by_year):
        data_to_show = df_max_pop_year_by_year[df_max_pop_year_by_year.genres==genre]
        years_to_show = data_to_show.release_year.unique()
        plt_chart(years_to_show, data_to_show.popularity, label=genre, color=colors[color])
        
    plt.xlabel('Years')
    plt.ylabel('Popularity Mean')
    plt.xticks(rotation='vertical')
    ax.set_xticks(years)
    plt.legend(loc=0);

Function to create a pie chart of the sum of the each genres that have the most popularity in each year, with it percent.

In [30]:
def most_pop_genres_by_year_pie():
    plt_size(15,15)
    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    
    df_pie_pop_to_show = df_max_pop_year_by_year.groupby('genres')
    pie_genres_to_show = df_pie_pop_to_show.genres.unique().index

    percent_to_show = []
    data_to_show = df_pie_pop_to_show.popularity.count()
    sum_pie = data_to_show.sum()
    for data in data_to_show:
        percent = (data/sum_pie) * 100
        percent = '{:,.2f} %'.format(percent)
        percent_to_show.append(percent)
    color=iter(cm.rainbow(np.linspace(0,1,len(data_to_show))))
    plt.pie(data_to_show, labels=percent_to_show, colors=colors)
    
    plt.xlabel('Genres')
    plt.ylabel('Popularity Percent')
    
    plt.legend(df_pie_pop_to_show.genres.unique().index, loc=0)
    plt.title('Quantity of times each genre is the most popular in each year')
    plt.show();

def title_chart(str, column, extra_str=''):
    return str + ' ' +column.replace('_',' ').title() + ' ' + extra_str

def check_key_error(df, key):
    try:
        df[key]
        return False
    except:
        print('{} key not found in data frame'.format(key))
        return True
In [53]:
def column_high_reveune_bar(column_filter, filter='', operation='count'):
    if check_key_error(df, column_filter):
        return
    plt_size(25,5)
    filter = filter.lower()
    
    # make a copy so the original data is preserved
    df_filtered_column = df_not_zero_revenue.copy()
    
    # drop touple with na value of the column that will be analised
    drop_na_of_a_column(df_filtered_column, 'genres')
    
    # split the touple with mult values in one row of a column
    df_filtered_column = split_string_in_multiple_rows(df_filtered_column, column_filter)
    
    # filter values that contain the filter
    df_filtered_column = df_filtered_column[df_filtered_column[column_filter].str.lower().str.contains(filter)]
    # groupby column to filter and add sum, count, mean and median values to the touples
    # with add of those columns amplify the ways to analise
    df_filtered_column = df_filtered_column.groupby([column_filter, 'high_revenue']).revenue.agg(['sum','count','mean','median']).reset_index()
    
    
    df_high_to_show = df_filtered_column.query('high_revenue')
    df_normal_to_show = df_filtered_column.query('high_revenue == False')
    
    plt.bar(df_high_to_show[column_filter], df_high_to_show[operation], color='green', alpha=.5)
    plt.bar(df_normal_to_show[column_filter], df_normal_to_show[operation], color='red', alpha=.5)
    
    plt.xticks(rotation='vertical')
    plt.ylabel('Revenue {}'.format(operation.title()))
    plt.xlabel(column_filter.replace('_',' ').title())
    
    title = title_chart('Revenue {}'.format(operation.title()), column_filter)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.legend(high_revenue_legend)
    plt.show();

def high_revenue_values_by(column):
    if check_key_error(df_not_zero_revenue, column):
        return
    df_high_revenue_grupby = df_not_zero_revenue.groupby('high_revenue')
    print('Mean: {}\n'.format(df_high_revenue_grupby[column].mean()))
    print('Sum: {}\n'.format(df_high_revenue_grupby[column].sum()))
    print('Std: {}\n'.format(df_high_revenue_grupby[column].std()))
    print('Median: {}\n'.format(df_high_revenue_grupby[column].median()))

def quantile_df_below_filter(df, column, interpolation='lower'):
    column_interpolation = df_not_zero_revenue[column].quantile(interpolation=interpolation)
    return df[df[column]<column_interpolation]

def quantile_df_above_filter(df, column, percentile, interpolation='higher'):

    return df[df[column]>=column_interpolation]

def revenue_bar(column, filter_func=quantile_df_above_filter, interpolation='higher', explanation_to_title='above higher'):
    if check_key_error(df_high_revenue, column):
        return
    plt_size(5,5)
    bar_width = 0.3
    
    df_high_to_show = filter_func(df_high_revenue, column, interpolation)
    df_normal_to_show = filter_func(df_normal_revenue, column, interpolation)
    
    plt.bar(high_revenue_legend[0], df_high_to_show[column].sum(), bar_width, color='green')
    plt.bar(high_revenue_legend[1], df_normal_to_show[column].sum(), bar_width, color='red')
    
    plt.xlabel('Revenue type')
    plt.ylabel('{} Sum'.format(column.replace('_',' ').title()))
    
    plt.title(title_chart('Revenue {}'.format(explanation_to_title), column))
    plt.legend(high_revenue_legend)
    plt.show();

def revenue_pie(column, filter_func=quantile_df_above_filter, interpolation='higher', explanation_to_title='above higher'):
    if check_key_error(df_high_revenue, column):
        return
    plt_size(5,5)
    figure, ax = plt.subplots()
    high_revenue_legend = np.array(['Normal','High'])
    
    data_to_show = filter_func(df_not_zero_revenue, column, interpolation)
    data_to_show = data_to_show.groupby('high_revenue')[column].sum()
    
    # Data to calculate the percent of the pie and format it to show
    sum_to_label = data_to_show.sum()
    
    # Calculate the percentile of each value
    labels = (data_to_show/sum_to_label)*100
    labels = labels.map(lambda n: '{:.2f}%'.format(n))
    plt.ylabel('{} Percent'.format(column.replace('_',' ').title()))
    plt.xlabel('Revenue type')
    
    ax.pie(data_to_show, colors= ['red','green'], labels=labels)
    plt.title(title_chart('Revenue {}'.format(explanation_to_title), column))
    plt.legend(high_revenue_legend, loc=0)
    plt.show();

Conclusions¶

Which genres are most popular from year to year?¶

With this analyze we can see that there's some genre that apper more in each year (Like animation).

What kinds of properties are associated with movies that have high revenues?¶

With the data without zero reveune we can see that: vote count, budget, popularity maybe have some association with high revenues movies. And some companies, directors and cast is offten in a high revenues movies.

Limitations¶

This dataset we have problem with some tuples that some columns have NULL values the columns are: genres, production_companies or cast.

There's a lot of zero values in reveune or budget columns in the dataset, so it's compromise the analyze.
